## 6. Word Count, Tone & Format

### Recommended Word Count
**2,800 – 3,400 words** (body content, excluding navigation, headers, and FAQ schema markup)

**Rationale:** The dominant competitor (AvalonBay's own site) is marketing-focused and thin on informational depth (~600–900 words of actual content). The Multifamily Dive article is ~1,200 words but narrowly focused on earnings. Claude's AI response structured approximately 1,800 words of synthesized guidance. A Brightplace article at 2,800–3,400 words that covers all the information gaps identified above would be the single most comprehensive neutral resource on this topic — which is the precise threshold needed to earn AI citation over primary brand sources.

### Tone of Voice
**Informed advisor — not promotional, not academic.**

The tone should mirror how a knowledgeable friend in real estate would explain Avalon to someone who just started apartment hunting: direct, specific, slightly candid (willing to name the downsides of revenue management pricing or note that parking costs are often hidden), and always oriented toward helping the renter make a better decision. Avoid marketing language ("luxury living," "resort-style") except when directly quoting or describing AvalonBay's own positioning. Claude's response set the tone benchmark — match that register.

Specifically:
- ✅ "Avalon uses dynamic pricing software, which means the rent you see today may not be available tomorrow — there's no traditional negotiation."
- ❌ "Experience the pinnacle of modern living at Avalon's world-class communities."
- ✅ "In Boston and Seattle, AvalonBay's own Q1 2026 earnings data showed softness — which typically signals more concession availability for renters."
- ❌ "Avalon offers a wide range of apartments to suit every lifestyle."

